@SP For purposes of this puzzle, yes, TOWN is a general term. 

In Illinois, we have incorporated Cities, Villages and Towns (townships). 

Chicago is a city and most of its suburbs are either cities or villages. The distinction is that a village board is elected at large, where as a city's board has districts (wards). Many counties in Illinois are divided into townships, which tile the county (no gaps). In a few cases, like the suburb of Cicero, the township provides municipal governance and thus it is the Town of Cicero. But much of Chicago's suburbia consists of villages that also lie within one or more townships. There are also unincorporated settlements that get their services (only) from the township.

@SP

Well, given that the agency that manages diplomacy is called "The State Department," I don't think that's the best example. The same word can have different meanings in different contexts.

But I get your point. That said, I'm generally of the opinion that clueing should be as precise and accurate as possible. The clue "municipality generally smaller than a city" would be much better clueing without changing the difficulty level

