@Steven M.
This may shock you, but New York is not in fact the center of the universe.

Out in the rest of the world, towns are smaller than cities. I grew up in a small town of about 3,000 people. It had exactly one traffic light. The nearest city was Sioux Falls, which had about 100,000 people. In my mind, a town has less than 10,000 people. Any more than that, and it's a city.

@Katie
In OP's defense he never said NY was the center of the universe. And as this is a NY newspaper, he's legitimately pointing out that in NYS town has a specific meaning which does not fit the clue. I first became aware of this from the town of Brookhaven, also on Long Island. It stretches from the north shore to the south including parts of the barrier islands. It has eight incorporated villages and all or part of approximately fifty unincorporated hamlets. In the rest of the world any one of those villages would be called a town or a small city. Many of the hamlets would be considered towns as well. 

I have no problem with the clue and answer, because in common use I would say most New Yorkers use town in the same sense you do (although given the density of the tristate area there's no way I'd consider a town of 10,000 a city). But  OP makes a legitimate point.

